By : Riya Kumari

  • Linear Regression and Hypothesis Testing
  • Conclusion

Introduction ¶

With climate change on the rise, the predictability of natural disasters has been quite challenging and their occurrences are on the rise. 2020 was a disastrous year as we saw many natural disasters like wildfires, hurricanes, rain ,and flooding all around the US. The impact of these disasters are devastating. They kill hundreds of people and destroy thousands of homes. People's lives are shaken up, they lose their livelihoods and businesses go under. An example of this is Merced Property & Casualty Co, an insurance company that was unable to payout those who had lost their homes because of the large number of homeowner policies who were affected by a wildfire.

image credit : https://www.climate.gov/media/11835

With an increasing number of natural disasters, we are starting to face larger economic losses. In the image above, we can see just how costly these disasters can be. But how might natural disasters affect the economy on a much larger scale and in the long term? Does it differ by state or country? This is our starting question that we will try to explore in this tutorial.

Moreover, will be focusing on two countries, US and Indonesia, and do an in-depth analysis on different US states. The reason I choose Indonesia is because it is a much smaller country than the US and it is also near the ring of fire which makes it prone to natural disasters. It will be interesting to compare effect of natural disasters in Indonesia to the US because of the differences between the two countries.

Getting Started with the Data ¶

When a disaster occurs, it is declared by the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA). FEMA helps people before, during, and after disasters. They have made some of their datasets public through multiple APIs that can be found on this page : https://www.fema.gov/about/openfema/data-sets. After reading through the descriptions of these datasets, we choose to move forward with their FemaWebDisasterDeclarations as it contains necessary information on when, where and what type of disaster took place.

There are many colums in the FemaWebDisasterDeclaration dataset. The ones that I am intesrested in are the following:

  • incidentType : describes the type of incident (Hurricane, Flood, Snow, Wildfire, etc)
  • declarationDate : date the disaster was declared
  • incidententBeginDate : date the disaster began
  • incidentEndDate : date the disaster ended
  • declarationType : defines whether the disaster is a "Major Disaster", "Emergency", etc.
  • state

Looking at just the five rows of the dataframe, I notice some missing values which are labeled as NaN. There can be more missing values so lets try to find which columns have missing data so we can handle them appropriately.

In [3]:

for column in fema_data:

  # Counting number of null values
  if fema_data[column].isnull().sum() > 0:
    print("percent of missing values for " + column + ": " + str(fema_data[column].isnull().sum()/fema_data[column].count().sum()))

percent of missing values for incidentEndDate: 0.10744781783681215
percent of missing values for closeoutDate: 0.25849056603773585

We notice that only two columns have missing data : incidentEndDate and closeoutDate. Because these are date columns that record a specific event in time, it would not be appropriate to approximate these values. Therefore, we will replace these with an arbitrary date value such as 1000-04-20 00:00:00+00:00. I cannot just replace with np.nan because we will be converting the date objects to datetime objects for easier data processing and np.nan creates type issues.

In [4]:
# Converting dates to dateTime objects for easier processing and analysis

fema_data['incidentBeginDate'] = pd.to_datetime(fema_data['incidentBeginDate'])

# Replacing the null values and fixing types
fema_data = fema_data.fillna(value = np.datetime64('1000-04-20 00:00:00+00:00'))

Out[22]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Number of disasters')

There is also a positive trend for disasters and year. Indonesia has a slow increase in number of disasters over the year. What I mean is that the number of disasters does not cross 20 until 2020 so the disasters haven't drastically increased after a specific year as it is with the US plot. 2020 also had the highest number of disasters, similar to the US plot, however Indonesia faced less than 30 disasters that year while the US had faced around 700,000.

It is important to note that Indonesia is much smaller than the US in terms of geographical size, which would explain why Indonesia sees fewer disasters. The difference can also be attributed to the fact that Fema(US data) has collected a lot more disaster data, mainly because it is the government agency responsible in the US, while the Indonesia disaster data was put together by a data scientist on Kaggle.

How might GDP differ based on the disasters occuring in the US and Indonesia?¶

We are trying to explore the impact natural disasters have on the economy. A good measure for economic growth is GDP(gross domestic product). Here we are going to look at GDP growth per year and the number of disasters occuring. We want to see if there is any pattern, correlation, or any kind of relation. To do so, we will create a line plot of both the gdp and disasters occuring over the years and examine the trend.

Exploring duration of a disaster vs GDP growth rate¶

In this part of our data exploration, we will be adding a column for the current real gdp and future real gdp(1 year later) of the state a disaster occured in. For example, Hurricane Irma occured in Florida in 2015. We will record the gdp of Florida in 2015 and in 2016. This way, we are mapping each disaster with its current and future gdp to be able to calculate the GDP growth rate which will make it easier for us to interpret the plots created.

$$\mathrm{GDP\,growth\,rate} = \frac{Future\,Real\,GDP\,+\,Original\,Real\,GDP}{Original\,Real\,GDP}$$
In [31]:
warnings.simplefilter(action="ignore", category=SettingWithCopyWarning)
# Pairing each disaster with state gdp 1 year later 

# Creating new column in us disasters dataframe
top_10_disastersData['futureGDP'] = pd.Series(dtype='float')
top_10_disastersData['currentGDP'] = pd.Series(dtype='float')

# Looping over the rows and adding the respective gdp 1 year later
for index, row in fema_data.iterrows():
  state = row['stateName']
  year = row['year'] - 1
  
  # Getting current GDP
  currentGDP = states_gdp[(states_gdp['GeoName'] == state) & (states_gdp['year'] == year)]
  currentGDP = currentGDP['value']

  # Getting GDP 1 year later
  year = row['year']
  gdp_1_year_later = states_gdp[(states_gdp['GeoName'] == state) & (states_gdp['year'] == year)]
  gdp_1_year_later = gdp_1_year_later['value']

  # if gdp_2_years_later == nan:
  #   data['GDP 2 years later'][index] = np.nan
  # else:
  top_10_disastersData['futureGDP'][index] = gdp_1_year_later
  top_10_disastersData['currentGDP'][index] = currentGDP
  

# We don't have gdp data for some American territories and for 2020, so I'm dropping the null valued gdp rows
states_gdp = states_gdp.dropna()
top_10_disastersData = top_10_disastersData.dropna()

Now that we have our currentGDP and futureGDP column, we will be adding in a column for the duration of a disaster. This will help us create plots that will relate the duration of a disaster with GDP growth rate. Essentially, what we are asking is whether the duration of a disaster has some affect on the economy. By using duration, we can measure impact of a disaster. We make the assumption that disasters that last longer do more damage.

In [33]:
# We will be dropping columns that don't have an actual end date
top_10_disastersData = top_10_disastersData[top_10_disastersData['incidentEndDate'] != np.datetime64('1000-04-20 00:00:00+00:00')]

# Calculating duration of disasters
top_10_disastersData['incidentEndDate'] = pd.to_datetime(top_10_disastersData['incidentEndDate'])
top_10_disastersData['duration'] = top_10_disastersData['incidentEndDate'] - top_10_disastersData['incidentBeginDate']
top_10_disastersData['duration'] = [x.days for x in top_10_disastersData['duration']]

# Calculating gdp growth rate
top_10_disastersData['GDP_growth_rate'] = (top_10_disastersData['futureGDP'] - top_10_disastersData['currentGDP']) / top_10_disastersData['currentGDP']

Linear Regression and Hypothesis Testing ¶

In this part of the tutorial, we will be do a hypothesis test to test whether there is a linear relation between duration of a disaster and gdp growth rate. We will be using statsmodels to create our linear regression models and conduct our hypothesis test.

In [61]:
import statsmodels.formula.api as smf

Step 1 : We must set our null and alternate hypothesis. Because we want to prove that duration does linearly affect gdp growth, our null hypothesis is that it doesn't. In other words, the slope of the regression line is 0 and we want to prove that it is non-zero for the regression to be linear.

$H_0$ Null Hypothesis : Duration of a disaster does not linearly affect gdp growth rate.

$H_1$ Alternate Hypothesis : Duration of a disaster does linearly affect gdp growth rate

Step 2 : We must decide on a significance level($\alpha$).

$\alpha = 0.05$

In [42]:
# fitting statistical model using R-style formula. More info : https://www.statsmodels.org/devel/example_formulas.html?highlight=formula 
model = smf.ols(formula='GDP_growth_rate ~ duration', data = top_10_disastersData)
results = model.fit()
results.summary()

Since the p-value is 0.027 is less than our significance level of $\alpha = 0.05$, we can reject our null hypothesis. However, notice that R-squared of 0.002 is very close to 0, hence the model explains none of the variability of the data around its mean.

Next, we can try considering different disaster types as the duration of a disaster depends on the kind of disaster. So we are going to add an interaction term: disasterType.

Linear Regression for Different Disaster Types

To learn more about how to use interaction terms with statsmodels: https://www.statsmodels.org/devel/example_formulas.html

model2 = smf.ols(formula='GDP_growth_rate ~ duration * C(incidentType)', data=top_10_disastersData)

We see that only durations of hurricanes(duration:C(incidentType)[T.Hurricane]) has a p-value less than significane level of 0.05 so we can reject the null hypothesis for just this one variable. The others we can not reject the null hypothesis as they have p-values greater than our significance level. R-squared of 0.043 is slightly better than our previous model however, it's closer to 0 and still not able to explain the variation in our data well. Lets try to plot a regression line for hurricanes to visualize the linear relation:

We do notice a slight positive linear relation. It seems a bit odd that the longer a hurricane, the less damaging it is on the economy. The fema disaster data we have used hurricanes declared as major disasters and those as federal emergencies. It could be that different states are impacted differently. Next, we could try adding state as an interaction variable as we know from our previous data exploration that each state recovers differently from disasters. For instance, we saw in our data analysis how Texas and Louisiana were affected by disasters. Texas didn't seem take a hit to their GDP, while Louisiana did.

Also we will filter our incident type to include just the top 3 disasters: fires, hurricanes, and severe-storms to keep our analysis simpler.

In [67]:
# Filtering disaster data to include just fires, hurricanes, and severe storms
data = top_10_disastersData[(top_10_disastersData['incidentType'] == 'Fire') | (top_10_disastersData['incidentType'] == 'Hurricane') | (top_10_disastersData['incidentType'] == 'Severe Storm(s)')]

# Creating our model
model3 = smf.ols(formula='GDP_growth_rate ~ duration * C(incidentType) * C(stateName) ', data=data, missing = 'drop')
results = model3.fit()

# Printing just the significant p-values
pvalues = results.pvalues.copy(deep=True)
pvalues = pvalues.dropna()
print(pvalues[pvalues < 0.05])

# Printing OLS Regression Results
summary = results.summary()
print(summary.tables[0])

Our linear regression equation was extremely large so we filtered by the terms that had p-values less than 0.05. The R-squared is quite small and still doesn't explain the variation in the data well enough.

We notice that the two way interaction between the following are statistically significant and so we can reject the null hypothesis for the following:

  • Delaware and Severe Storms
  • Hawaii and Hurricanes
  • North Dakota and Severe Storms
  • Delaware and duration
  • Mississippi and duration
  • New York and duration

The three way interaction between New York, hurricane, and duration is also statistically significant and we can reject the null hypothesis here as well.

This means that state and type of disaster plays a role in determining the effect duration of a disaster may have on the GDP growth rate.

Findings and Conclusion ¶

Through our exploratory analysis some of our findings were :

  • Natural disasters have been drastically rising since 2000
  • In the US , there is an increase in the number of fires, hurricanes, and severe storms while in Indonesia there's been an increase in floods
  • Natural disasters impacts the local economy of the US instead of the country's economy as a whole

After conducting the hypothesis test and linear regression we found there to be some kind of relation between the duration of a disaster and the effect on GDP growth in the US, however this relation depends on the US state and type of disaster.

These findings provoke new questions, such as what effect might the strength of a disaster have, or if state and federal funding is helping. The Fema dataset consists of more than just disaster information. It has information on assistance programs, hazard mitigation, and emergency management. One can explore a lot more.

Disasters are increasing and are becoming much worse because of climate change. They aren't exactly easy to predict either so it is important to be prepared. I hope you found this tutorial useful in understanding the data science pipeline and are able to further this research.
